  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "# Core Operations: Pixel Manipulation and ROI\n",
    "\n",
    "This notebook explores fundamental, low-level operations in OpenCV. We will learn how to access and manipulate individual pixel values and how to work with a 'Region of Interest' (ROI)."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "### Step 1: Setup\n",
    "\n",
    "First, we import the necessary libraries and define the path to our shared assets folder."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "import cv2\n",
    "import numpy as np\n",
    "import os\n",
    "\n",
    "# Define the relative path to the assets directory\n",
    "assets_path = os.path.join('..', '_assets')"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "### Step 2: Accessing Individual Pixel Values\n",
    "\n",
    "Images loaded in OpenCV are NumPy arrays. You can access the color value of a specific pixel by using its row and column coordinates.\n",
    "\n",
    "Remember: OpenCV loads color images in **BGR (Blue, Green, Red)** order by default."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "img_path = os.path.join(assets_path, 'basketball.jpg')\n",
    "image = cv2.imread(img_path)\n",
    "\n",
    "if image is not None:\n",
    "    # Access the pixel at row 100, column 100\n",
    "    pixel_value = image[100, 100]\n",
    "    \n",
    "    print(f"Image Shape: {image.shape}")\n",
    "    print(f"BGR value at (100, 100): {pixel_value}")\n",
    "else:\n",
    "    print(f"Error: Could not load image from {img_path}")"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "### Step 3: Modifying Pixel Values\n",
    "\n",
    "Just as you can access a pixel's value, you can also change it by assigning a new value to that coordinate."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "img_path = os.path.join(assets_path, 'cat.jpg')\n",
    "image = cv2.imread(img_path)\n",
    "\n",
    "if image is not None:\n",
    "    print(f"Original pixel value at (100, 150): {image[150, 100]}")\n",
    "\n",
    "    # Change the pixel at row 150, column 100 to RED\n",
    "    # BGR format means red is [0, 0, 255]\n",
    "    image[150, 100] = [0, 0, 255]\n",
    "    \n",
    "    print(f"New pixel value at (100, 150): {image[150, 100]}")\n",
    "\n",
    "    # Display the image to see the single red pixel\n",
    "    cv2.imshow("Modified Cat", image)\n",
    "    cv2.waitKey(0)\n",
    "    cv2.destroyAllWindows()\n",
    "else:\n",
    "    print(f"Error: Could not load image from {img_path}")"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "### Step 4: Region of Interest (ROI)\n",
    "\n",
    "A Region of Interest (ROI) is a specific rectangular area of an image that you want to work on. Using NumPy's array slicing capabilities, you can easily select and manipulate these regions.\n",
    "\n",
    "The slicing format is `image[startY:endY, startX:endX]`."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "img_path = os.path.join(assets_path, 'forest.jpg')\n",
    "image = cv2.imread(img_path)\n",
    "\n",
    "if image is not None:\n",
    "    # Define the coordinates for the ROI\n",
    "    x1, y1 = 150, 100\n",
    "    x2, y2 = 400, 300\n",
    "    \n",
    "    # Extract the ROI from the image\n",
    "    roi = image[y1:y2, x1:x2]\n",
    "    \n",
    "    # Display the original image and the extracted ROI\n",
    "    cv2.imshow("Original Forest", image)\n",
    "    cv2.imshow("Extracted ROI", roi)\n",
    "    cv2.waitKey(0)\n",
    "    cv2.destroyAllWindows()\n",
    "else:\n",
    "    print(f"Error: Could not load image from {img_path}")"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "#### Modifying an ROI\n",
    "\n",
    "You can also modify an entire ROI at once. When you select an ROI, it is a 'view' into the original image's data, not a copy. This means that any changes made to the ROI will be reflected in the original image."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "img_path = os.path.join(assets_path, 'forest.jpg')\n",
    "image = cv2.imread(img_path)\n",
    "\n",
    "if image is not None:\n",
    "    # Select the same ROI\n",
    "    roi = image[100:300, 150:400]\n",
    "    \n",
    "    # Change the color of the ROI to solid blue\n",
    "    roi[:, :] = [255, 0, 0] # BGR for Blue\n",
    "    \n",
    "    # Display the original image to see the change\n",
    "    cv2.imshow("Modified Forest with Blue ROI", image)\n",
    "    cv2.waitKey(0)\n",
    "    cv2.destroyAllWindows()\n",
    "else:\n",
    "    print(f"Error: Could not load image from {img_path}")"
   ]
  }
 ],
